            <LEXSense LanguageCode="en" LastEdited="2021-07-22 10:25:43" LastEditedBy="">
              <DefinitionLong/>
              <DefinitionShort>any living creature, whether wild or domesticated (in contrast with plants)</DefinitionShort>
              <Glosses>
                <Gloss>living creature</Gloss>
                <Gloss>animal</Gloss>
              </Glosses>
              <Comments>In a number of languages the equivalent of ‘living things’ or ‘living creatures’ is simply ‘those which are alive’ or ‘those that move about.’ ζῷον[a], therefore, includes essentially quadrupeds, fish, birds, and insects, and is not used in the NT to designate human beings. In several passages in the book of Revelation, ζῷον[b] ‘a living being’ ({D:12.32}) is employed to refer to supernatural beings at God’s throne (note {S:06600400600000-06600400900000} which in many ways is similar to the description of ‘living creatures’ in {S:02600100500000}f).</Comments>
            </LEXSense>
